    {
      "role": "user",
      "content": "That makes sense. You mentioned the blockage issue—what kind of stuff actually causes those blockages in real life? Like, is it just dirt or something else that pilots have to look out for during pre-flight?",
      "source": "evaluator"
    },
    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "Blockages on a pitot tube, or any airspeed sensor, are a real hazard, and they can come from a surprising variety of sources. You've got the obvious stuff, like dust, grit, or even insect nests, which are the mundane annoyances of flying. Sometimes, the wind can just blow a little bit of debris—maybe a stray piece of dried mud, or even a tiny, forgotten twig—right into the opening.\n\nHowever, it's not *just* dirt, though. Sometimes, icing is the real villain, especially when flying in those damp, cold conditions. Ice can build up inside the tube, effectively sealing it off, which is far more serious than a simple speck of dirt. Pilots need to be vigilant about checking for ice buildup, especially before heading into known icing zones, because a frozen pitot tube is functionally the same as a completely clogged one—a dead sensor.\n\nYou should also be mindful of things like bird droppings, which, while perhaps less common than dust, can be surprisingly adhesive and create a perfect seal. It's a constant battle against the environment, which is why pre-flight checks are so important. You need to inspect those tubes thoroughly, making sure they",
      "source": "target",
